chr1	1	121000000	Partial monosomy 1p	loss	Partial monosomy 1p is associated with a segmental deletion associated with developmental delay/intellectual disability, dysmorphism, and organ/system anomalies depending on the region involved. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same chromosomal change. (OMIM: —)
chr1	834083	6289973	1p36 terminal region (includes GABRD)	gain	Though there have been several reports of duplications and triplications within 1p36, the phenotypes reported have been inconsistent. This is likely due to differences in duplication size and location within 1p36 between patients, as well as the presence or absence of other genomic imbalances. Interpretations of these duplications should be made in the context of the individual clinical presentation and the specific gene(s) involved.
chr1	834083	6289973	1p36 terminal region (includes GABRD)	loss	1p36 Deletion Syndrome is associated with Most common terminal microdeletion (1p36.13–1p36.33). Features developmental delay, ID, hypotonia, seizures, cardiomyopathy/CHD, hearing/vision problems, characteristic facial features. Severity varies with deletion size; multiple genes implicated (RERE, PRDM16, SKI, HNRNPU). Key genes: RERE; PRDM16; SKI; HNRNPU. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same deletion. (OMIM: 607872)
chr1	142600001	155000000	Monosomy 1q21-q32	loss	Monosomy 1q21-q32 is associated with a chromosomal deletion affecting the specified segment, associated with developmental delay, intellectual disability, congenital anomalies, and variable craniofacial/somatic features. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same chromosomal change. (OMIM: —)
chr1	146577486	147394506	1q21.1 recurrent region (distal, BP3-BP4) (includes GJA5)	gain	Though there have been several reports of duplications and triplications within 1p36, the phenotypes reported have been inconsistent. This is likely due to differences in duplication size and location within 1p36 between patients, as well as the presence or absence of other genomic imbalances. Interpretations of these duplications should be made in the context of the individual clinical presentation and the specific gene(s) involved.
chr1	146577486	147394506	1q21.1 recurrent region (distal, BP3-BP4) (includes GJA5)	loss	1q21.1 Neuro is associated with Distal 1q21.1 deletion associated with microcephaly, CHD (GJA5), cataracts (GJA8), DD/ID, and increased risk for ASD/ADHD/schizophrenia. Variable expressivity. Key genes: GJA5; GJA8. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same deletion. (OMIM: 612474)
chr1	156500001	249250621	Trisomy 1q23-qter	gain	Trisomy 1q23-qter is associated with a chromosomal duplication of the specified segment, associated with developmental delay, learning difficulties, growth differences, and variable congenital anomalies. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same chromosomal change. (OMIM: —)
chr1	224100001	249250621	Monosomy 1q42-qter	loss	Monosomy 1q42-qter is associated with a chromosomal deletion affecting the specified segment, associated with developmental delay, intellectual disability, congenital anomalies, and variable craniofacial/somatic features. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same chromosomal change. (OMIM: —)
chr1	243287730	245318287	1q43q44 terminal region (includes AKT3)	loss	1q43–q44 Microdeletion is associated with Causes DD/ID, microcephaly, callosal anomalies, epilepsy. Genes: AKT3 (brain size/CC), HNRNPU (epilepsy), ZBTB18 (callosal defects). Key genes: AKT3; HNRNPU; ZBTB18. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same deletion. (OMIM: 612337)
