chr4	331568	2010962	4p16.3 terminal (Wolf-Hirschhorn syndrome) region	gain	A limited number of patients with isolated duplications affecting this region of 4p16.3 are reported in the literature and there is variability in duplication breakpoints across these patients. The clinical phenotypes included macrocephaly, tall stature, developmental and speech delay, and minor anomalies.
chr4	331568	2010962	4p16.3 terminal (Wolf-Hirschhorn syndrome) region	loss	Wolf–Hirschhorn Syndrome (4p16.3) is associated with Contiguous-gene deletion at 4p16.3 causes growth retardation, severe DD/ID, seizures, hypotonia, midline/craniofacial ‘Greek warrior helmet’ features, and multiple congenital anomalies; critical region includes WHSC1/LETM1. Key genes: NSD2 (WHSC1); LETM1; FGFRL1. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same deletion. (OMIM: 194190)
