chr5	37693	11347262	5p15 terminal (Cri du chat syndrome) region	gain	"Duplications of this precisely defined region of terminal 5p have not been described but there are rare reports of patients with smaller or larger duplication, some of whom also have deletions of 5p material as well. Vust, et al. (2002, PMID:12030892) report a patient with a maternally inherited duplication at 5p15.3 that does not include the ""Cri du Chat critical region"" at 5p15.2. This patient had mild dysmorphic features and neurodevelopmental problems, but also had prenatal alcohol exposure. Her mother had a probable learning disability and mental health concerns. The clinical assessment of the duplication was complicated by the family's difficult social situation. "
chr5	37693	11347262	5p15 terminal (Cri du chat syndrome) region	loss	Cri-du-chat (5p15) is associated with Terminal/interstitial deletions of 5p15 cause high‑pitched cat‑like cry, microcephaly, DD/ID, hypotonia, facial dysmorphism, and congenital anomalies; size and inclusion of 5p15.3/5p15.2 influence speech and cognitive outcomes. Key genes: CTNND2; TERT. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same deletion. (OMIM: 123450)
chr5	50017031	180793266	Partial monosomy 5q	loss	Partial monosomy 5q is associated with a segmental deletion associated with developmental delay/intellectual disability, dysmorphism, and organ/system anomalies depending on the region involved. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same chromosomal change. (OMIM: —)
