chr5	175728979	177047793	5q35 recurrent (Sotos syndrome) region (includes NSD1)	gain	The recurrent 5q35 duplication including NSD1 is associated with short stature, microcephaly, delayed bone age, and developmental delay/intellectual disability. This duplication has been observed to occur both de novo and inherited. When inherited, carrier parents present with milder features, including learning disability/intellectual disability. Available case-control comparison studies have a limited number of cases and have not shown enrichment of this duplication in clinical populations.
chr5	175728979	177047793	5q35 recurrent (Sotos syndrome) region (includes NSD1)	loss	Sotos Syndrome (5q35) is associated with NSD1 haploinsufficiency causes overgrowth with advanced bone age, macrocephaly, DD/ID, characteristic facies, and variable congenital anomalies; cancer risk is modestly increased. Key genes: NSD1. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same deletion. (OMIM: 117550)
