chr7	5536848	5799722	7p22.1 region (includes ACTB)	loss	7p22.1 Microdeletion is associated with 7p22.1 microdeletions associate with DD/ID, speech delay, behavioral problems, and minor dysmorphism; some patients have heart/kidney defects. Key genes: ACTB. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same deletion. (OMIM: 102630 )
chr7	72744455	74142510	7q11.23 recurrent (Williams-Beuren syndrome) region (includes ELN)	gain	Duplication of this region is associated with Duplication 7q11.23 syndrome. There is sufficient evidence to support the triplosensitivity of this region. Clinical findings in duplication 7q11.23 syndrome may include: speech delay, autistic features (PMID: 21658581), motor delay, seizures, hypotonia, brain anomalies, joint laxity, and craniofacial abnormalities. Various cardiovascular abnormalities have also been reported in patients with the 7q11.23 microduplication syndrome.
chr7	72744455	74142510	7q11.23 recurrent (Williams-Beuren syndrome) region (includes ELN)	loss	Williams–Beuren Syndrome (7q11.23) is associated with Typical 1.5–1.8 Mb 7q11.23 deletion causes characteristic facies, supravalvular aortic stenosis (ELN), intellectual disability with visuospatial weakness, overfriendly personality, and endocrine/CT anomalies. Key genes: ELN; GTF2I; GTF2IRD1; LIMK1. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same deletion. (OMIM: 194050)
chr7	75158048	76063176	7q11.23 recurrent distal region (includes HIP1, YWHAG)	loss	Evidence in support of the pathogenicity of the recurrent 7q11.23 distal region deletion is emerging at this time. Deletions of this region have been reported in 10 patients with neurodevelopmental phenotypes, including seizures. Most of the reported deletions have been inherited from similarly affected parents, though it has also been found to represent a de novo event.
