chr10	81682843	88739388	10q22.3q23.2 recurrent region (includes BMPR1A)	loss	10q22–q23 Syndrome is associated with deletions across 10q22–q23 associated with DD/ID, seizures, dysmorphic features, and variable anomalies; BMPR1A/PTEN genes implicated in cancer predisposition. Key genes: BMPR1A; PTEN. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same deletion. (OMIM: 612242)
chr11	1	51869973	Partial trisomy 11p	gain	Partial trisomy 11p is associated with a segmental duplication associated with developmental delay/learning difficulties, hypotonia, and variable congenital anomalies depending on the region involved. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same chromosomal change. (OMIM: —)
chr11	31803509	32510988	11p13 (WAGR syndrome) region	loss	WAGR (11p13) is associated with Classical WAGR syndrome due to WT1 and PAX6 haploinsufficiency: Wilms tumor risk, aniridia, GU anomalies, and developmental delay. Key genes: WT1; PAX6. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same deletion. (OMIM: 194072)
chr11	43894800	46152450	11p11.2 (Potocki-Shaffer syndrome) region (includes ALX4, EXT2)	loss	Potocki-Shaffer Syndrome (11p11.2) is associated with Caused by deletion at 11p11.2 including ALX4 and EXT2; features multiple exostoses, parietal foramina, DD/ID, hypotonia, craniofacial dysmorphism, and seizures. Key genes: ALX4; EXT2. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same deletion. (OMIM: 601224)
chr11	55755704	135006515	Partial monosomy 11q	loss	Partial monosomy 11q is associated with a segmental deletion associated with developmental delay/intellectual disability, dysmorphism, and organ/system anomalies depending on the region involved. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same chromosomal change. (OMIM: —)
chr11	55755704	135006515	Partial trisomy 11q	gain	Partial trisomy 11q is associated with a segmental duplication associated with developmental delay/learning difficulties, hypotonia, and variable congenital anomalies depending on the region involved. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same chromosomal change. (OMIM: —)
chr11	67763646	71236931	11q13.2q13.4 recurrent region (includes SHANK2, FGFs)	loss	11q13 Microdeletion is associated with Interstitial 11q13 deletions associated with DD/ID, speech delay, hearing loss, and variable malformations; SHANK2 gene often implicated. Key genes: SHANK2. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same deletion. (OMIM: 613436)
chr11	110470724	121170709	Jacobsen syndrome	loss	None
chr12	1	33713547	Partial monosomy 12p	loss	Partial monosomy 12p is associated with a segmental deletion associated with developmental delay/intellectual disability, dysmorphism, and organ/system anomalies depending on the region involved. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same chromosomal change. (OMIM: —)
chr12	1	33713547	Partial trisomy 12p	gain	Partial trisomy 12p is associated with a segmental duplication associated with developmental delay/learning difficulties, hypotonia, and variable congenital anomalies depending on the region involved. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same chromosomal change. (OMIM: —)
chr12	38200000	133851895	Partial trisomy 12q	gain	Partial trisomy 12q is associated with a segmental duplication associated with developmental delay/learning difficulties, hypotonia, and variable congenital anomalies depending on the region involved. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same chromosomal change. (OMIM: —)
chr13	40100001	55300000	Monosomy 13q14	loss	Monosomy 13q14 is associated with a chromosomal deletion affecting the specified segment, associated with developmental delay, intellectual disability, congenital anomalies, and variable craniofacial/somatic features. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same chromosomal change. (OMIM: —)
chr13	40100001	55300000	Trisomy 13cen-q14	gain	Trisomy 13cen-q14 is associated with a chromosomal duplication of the specified segment, associated with developmental delay, learning difficulties, growth differences, and variable congenital anomalies. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same chromosomal change. (OMIM: —)
chr13	55300001	115169878	Monosomy 13q21-qter	loss	Monosomy 13q21-qter is associated with a chromosomal deletion affecting the specified segment, associated with developmental delay, intellectual disability, congenital anomalies, and variable craniofacial/somatic features. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same chromosomal change. (OMIM: —)
chr13	55300001	115169878	Trisomy 13q21-qter	gain	Trisomy 13q21-qter is associated with a chromosomal duplication of the specified segment, associated with developmental delay, learning difficulties, growth differences, and variable congenital anomalies. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same chromosomal change. (OMIM: —)
chr14	1	107349540	Partial trisomy 14	gain	Partial trisomy 14 is associated with a segmental duplication associated with developmental delay/learning difficulties, hypotonia, and variable congenital anomalies depending on the region involved. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same chromosomal change. (OMIM: —)
chr14	21826900	21861987	14q11.2 region including CHD8 and SUPT16H	loss	14q11.2 region including CHD8 and SUPT16H is associated with CNVs at 14q11.2 have been reported with developmental delay, autism spectrum disorder, and neuropsychiatric features. Key genes: CHD8; SUPT16H. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same deletion. (OMIM: 613457)
chr14	67900001	107349540	Trisomy 14q24-qter	gain	Trisomy 14q24-qter is associated with a chromosomal duplication of the specified segment, associated with developmental delay, learning difficulties, growth differences, and variable congenital anomalies. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same chromosomal change. (OMIM: —)
chr14	101190852	101299552	DLK1-MEG3 Intergenic Region	loss	DLK1-MEG3 Intergenic Region is associated with Alterations in the imprinted DLK1-MEG3 domain at 14q32 can disturb imprinting and are associated with Temple syndrome or Kagami–Ogata syndrome phenotypes. Key genes: DLK1; MEG3. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same deletion. (OMIM: 606587)
chr15	1	102531392	Supernumerary inv dup (15)	gain	Supernumerary inv dup (15) is associated with a supernumerary inverted duplication chromosome, typically resulting in partial tetrasomy of 15q, associated with hypotonia, developmental delay, autism spectrum features, and seizures in some individuals. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same chromosomal change. (OMIM: —)
chr15	22832519	23090897	15q11.2 recurrent region (BP1-BP2) (includes NIPA1)	loss	15q11.2 BP1–BP2 Microdeletion is associated with Recurrent susceptibility CNV linked to variable neurodevelopmental phenotypes (speech delay, learning difficulties, ADHD/ASD) with reduced penetrance. Key genes: NIPA1; NIPA2; CYFIP1; TUBGCP5. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same deletion. (OMIM: 615656)
chr15	23747996	28379874	15q11.2q13 recurrent (PWS/AS) region (Class I, BP1-BP3 and Class II, BP2-BP3)	gain	Duplication (or triplication) of the 15q11.2q13 recurrent (BP1-BP3 or BP2-BP3) region is associated with overlapping clinical phenotypes that vary in clinical severity dependent upon parent of origin and copy number state. Maternally derived duplications are associated with clinical findings including hypotonia and motor delays, developmental delay/intellectual disability (DD/ID), autism spectrum disorders (ASD), seizures, dysmorphic features, behavioral difficulties, and psychiatric disorders (including schizophrenia). Paternally derived duplications are less described in the literature but have been reported in association with milder clinical phenotypes including DD, dysmorphic features, ASD, and seizures.
chr15	23747996	28379874	15q11.2q13 recurrent (PWS/AS) region (Class I, BP1-BP3 and Class II, BP2-BP3)	loss	Angelman / Prader–Willi BP2–3 (15q11.2–q13.1) is associated with Deletions spanning BP2–BP3 underlie most typical AS/PWS cases (maternal vs paternal origin determines phenotype). Key genes: UBE3A; SNRPN cluster; GABRB3/GABRA5/GABRG3. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same deletion. (OMIM: 176270, 105830 )
chr15	31192889	32445405	15q13.3 recurrent region (BP4-BP5) (includes CHRNA7)	loss	15q13.3 (BP4–BP5) Microdeletion is associated with Recurrent 15q13.3 microdeletion associated with DD/ID, epilepsy, neuropsychiatric disorders, and variable dysmorphism; reduced penetrance. Key genes: CHRNA7. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same deletion. (OMIM: 612001)
chr15	32019621	32445405	15q13.3 recurrent region (D-CHRNA7 to BP5) (includes CHRNA7, OTUD7A)	loss	CHRNA7 (15q13.3) Focal Deletion is associated with Exonic deletions of CHRNA7 alone confer risk for epilepsy, cognitive/behavioral disorders, and ASD with incomplete penetrance. Key genes: CHRNA7. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same deletion. (OMIM: 612001)
chr15	59100001	102531392	Trisomy 15q22-qter	gain	Trisomy 15q22-qter is associated with a chromosomal duplication of the specified segment, associated with developmental delay, learning difficulties, growth differences, and variable congenital anomalies. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same chromosomal change. (OMIM: —)
chr15	72963715	75508312	15q24 recurrent region (LCR A-LCR C)	loss	15q24 AC is associated with Same core phenotype as 15q24 microdeletion with AC breakpoints; neurodevelopmental and urogenital anomalies common. Key genes: SIN3A. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same deletion. (OMIM: 613406)
chr15	72963715	75972909	15q24 recurrent region (LCR A-LCR D) (includes SIN3A)	loss	15q24 AB is associated with 15q24 microdeletion syndrome—growth restriction, DD/ID, facial dysmorphism, genital anomalies, and limb/skeletal features; breakpoints define AB subtype. Key genes: SIN3A; BCL2L10 (region). Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same deletion. (OMIM: 613406)
chr15	75631787	75972909	15q24 recurrent region (LCR C-LCR D) (includes SIN3A)	loss	Witteveen–Kolk Syndrome (15q24 CD) is associated with Haploinsufficiency of SIN3A causes a syndromic neurodevelopmental disorder with ID, hypotonia, speech delay, behavioral issues, and facial features. Key genes: SIN3A. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same deletion. (OMIM: 613406)
chr15	83199987	84714733	15q25.2 recurrent region (proximal, LCR-A/B-C) (includes RPS17)	loss	Deletion of the 15q25.2 recurrent proximal LCR-A/B to -C region is associated with a phenotype that typically includes developmental delay/intellectual disability, anemia, short stature, mild facial dysmorphisms and additional variable findings. Within the deleted region, the haploinsufficient gene RPS17, associated with Diamond-Blackfan anemia (DBA), is considered to be a major contributor to the phenotype of this deletion.
chr16	1	34728394	Partial trisomy 16p	gain	Partial trisomy 16p is associated with a segmental duplication associated with developmental delay/learning difficulties, hypotonia, and variable congenital anomalies depending on the region involved. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same chromosomal change. (OMIM: —)
chr16	3775056	3930121	16p13.3 region (includes CREBBP)	loss	Rubinstein–Taybi Syndrome (16p13.3) is associated with Classic RTS due to CREBBP (or EP300) haploinsufficiency: broad thumbs/halluces, characteristic facies, short stature, DD/ID, and congenital anomalies. Key genes: CREBBP. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same deletion. (OMIM: 180849)
chr16	15511711	16292265	16p13.11 recurrent region (BP1-BP3, BP2-BP3, or BP2-BP4) (includes MYH11)	gain	Duplication of the 16p13.11 region has been associated with a variable clinical presentation. Features observed in carrier patients referred for clinical genome wide copy number testing have been relatively nonspecific including developmental delay, intellectual disability/learning difficulties, behavioral abnormalities (including autism and ADHD), and variable dysmorphic features, which are also generally common in the patient population referred for clinical copy number analysis. The majority of patients with this duplication have inherited it, with most coming from an apparently unaffected parent.
chr16	15511711	16292265	16p13.11 recurrent region (BP1-BP3, BP2-BP3, or BP2-BP4) (includes MYH11)	loss	16p13.11 BP I–III is associated with Extended rearrangements encompassing BP I–III show similar neurodevelopmental risk with broader gene content and variable expressivity. Key genes: NDE1; MYH11; ABCC6. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same deletion. (OMIM: 160745 )
chr16	21948445	22430804	16p12.2 recurrent region (proximal) (includes EEF2K, CDR2)	loss	Deletion of the 16p12.2 recurrent proximal (BP2-BP3) region has been observed in the clinical population in association with highly variable and nonspecific phenotypes including developmental delay/intellectual disability, speech delay, and psychiatric and behavioral abnormalities. Assessments of 16p12.2 deletion carriers identified from the general population have so far shown significant effects for a single measure of neurocognitive domain subclinical phenotypes across multiple studies. In the clinical setting, the 16p12.2 recurrent deletion is almost always inherited from an apparently unaffected or mildly affected parent.
chr16	28822635	29046499	16p11.2 recurrent region (distal, BP2-BP3) (includes SH2B1)	loss	Deletion of the 16p11.2 distal region is associated with variable and incompletely penetrant phenotypes that most often include obesity, macrocephaly, and developmental delay/intellectual disability and less frequently include autism, behavioral difficulties, non-specific craniofacial dysmorphism, and schizophrenia.
chr16	29649997	30199852	16p11.2 recurrent region (proximal, BP4-BP5) (includes TBX6)	gain	Clinical features associated with 16p11.2 (TBX6) proximal region duplication may include: developmental delays (including speech, language and motor delays), intellectual disability, autism spectrum disorder, behavioral problems (including ADHD), psychiatric disorders, seizures, microcephaly, decreased body mass index, congenital anomalies, and additional variable clinical findings. Incomplete penetrance has been observed.
chr16	29649997	30199852	16p11.2 recurrent region (proximal, BP4-BP5) (includes TBX6)	loss	Clinical features associated with 16p11.2 (TBX6) proximal region deletion may include: developmental delay; cognitive impairment; language delay; autism spectrum disorder; delayed language development (with more receptive than expressive language abilities); minor dysmorphic facial features that do not represent a consistent, recognizable pattern; neurologic issues including seizures or electroencephalogram abnormalities; obesity; psychiatric diseases; and cardiac malformations. Incomplete penetrance has been observed.
chr16	38600001	90354753	Partial monosomy 16q	loss	Partial monosomy 16q is associated with a segmental deletion associated with developmental delay/intellectual disability, dysmorphism, and organ/system anomalies depending on the region involved. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same chromosomal change. (OMIM: —)
chr16	38600001	90354753	Partial trisomy 16q	gain	Partial trisomy 16q is associated with a segmental duplication associated with developmental delay/learning difficulties, hypotonia, and variable congenital anomalies depending on the region involved. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same chromosomal change. (OMIM: —)
chr17	1	50200000	Trisomy 17pter-q21	gain	Trisomy 17pter-q21 is associated with a chromosomal duplication of the specified segment, associated with developmental delay, learning difficulties, growth differences, and variable congenital anomalies. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same chromosomal change. (OMIM: —)
chr17	1247833	2588909	17p13.3 (Miller-Dieker syndrome) region (includes YWHAE and PAFAH1B1)	gain	Duplication of this region (involving both YWHAE and LIS1 genes) is associated with a variable clinical phenotype that typically includes structural brain abnormalities (involving the corpus callosum, cerebellar vermis, and cranial base), hypotonia, intellectual disability, a relatively distinct facial phenotype, and other variable findings (summarized by Curry et al., 2013, PMID 23813913)
chr17	1247833	2588909	17p13.3 (Miller-Dieker syndrome) region (includes YWHAE and PAFAH1B1)	loss	Miller–Dieker Syndrome (17p13.3) is associated with Classical lissencephaly with distinctive facies due to deletion of LIS1 (PAFAH1B1) and adjacent genes; severe DD, seizures, and structural brain malformations. Key genes: PAFAH1B1 (LIS1); YWHAE. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same deletion. (OMIM: 247200)
chr17	14097915	15422952	17p12 recurrent (HNPP/CMT1A) region (includes PMP22)	gain	Duplication of the 17p12 recurrent region is associated with Charcot-Marie-Tooth type 1A (CMT1A). CMT1A is a demyelinating neuropathy, characterized by slowly progressive weakness and atrophy of distal muscles (with legs typically more frequently and severely affected than arms), hearing loss, pes cavus foot deformity, hip dysplasia, and additional clinical findings. Age of onset ranges from the first to third decades of life; severity of the condition is variable, with some carriers not clinically recognized. Within the duplicated region, the gene PMP22 is considered to be the main contributor to the phenotypes associated with this duplication.. (OMIM: 118220 / 162500)
chr17	14097915	15422952	17p12 recurrent (HNPP/CMT1A) region (includes PMP22)	loss	Deletion of the 17p12 recurrent region is associated with hereditary neuropathy with liability to pressure palsies (HNPP). Clinical findings in HNPP include recurrent acute sensory and motor neuropathy in a single or multiple nerves, typically beginning in adolescence or young adulthood. Men with 17p12 recurrent deletions typically have more severe clinical and electrophysiological manifestations of HNPP. Variable expressivity for HNPP in 17p12 carriers has been observed, even within the same family. Within the deleted region, the haploinsufficient gene PMP22 is considered to be the main contributor to phenotypes associated with this deletion.
chr17	16810028	20213202	17p11.2 recurrent (SMS/PLS) region (includes RAI1)	gain	Duplications of this region cause Potocki-Lupski syndrome and are mediated by segmental duplications.
chr17	16810028	20213202	17p11.2 recurrent (SMS/PLS) region (includes RAI1)	loss	Deletions of this region are a recurrent cause of Smith-Magenis syndrome (SMS) and are mediated by segmental duplications. Mutations in the RAI1 gene have been identified in patients with Smith-Magenis syndrome and haploinsufficiency of this gene is believed to be responsible for the majority of this phenotype. While there is some variability in the size of deletions associated with SMS, due to multiple segmental duplications in the region, all deletions contain the RAI1 gene.
chr17	29097069	30264027	17q11.2 recurrent region (includes NF1)	gain	Duplication of the 17q11.2 recurrent region has been reported in over 10 independent families (approximately 17 patients). Clinical findings that are consistently observed include developmental delay/intellectual disability and mild facial dysmorphisms. Additional findings have been reported in a few patients including seizures, dental enamel hypoplasia, early onset baldness, short stature, and failure to thrive, although these findings are not consistently observed across all patients. Parental testing has demonstrated that four out of six of the reported duplications were inherited, and that most are inherited from an affected parent; however, two families have also been found to have unaffected carriers. Case-control studies have shown enrichment of this duplication in the clinical population.
chr17	29097069	30264027	17q11.2 recurrent region (includes NF1)	loss	Deletion of the 17q11.2 recurrent region, encompassing the gene Neurofibromin 1 and other neighboring genes, is associated with neurofibromatosis type I (NF1). This deletion accounts for approximately 5% cases of NF1. Although patients with the 17q11.2 deletion show a variable clinical phenotype, similar to patients with gene-level pathogenic variants, genotype-phenotype correlation studies have shown that 17q11.2 deletion carriers may have larger numbers and earlier appearance of cutaneous neurofibromas, higher incidence and more severe cognitive abnormalities, facial dysmorphisms, and overgrowth (PMID: 20301288). Genotype-phenotype correlations across different 17q11.2 deletion types have not yet been demonstrated. Approximately 17% of patients with the recurrent 17q11.2 deletion have inherited it from a parent (PMID: 20513137). Deletions of this region are enriched within the clinical population (summarized below). (OMIM: 613113)
chr17	34815072	36192489	17q12 recurrent (RCAD syndrome) region (includes HNF1B)	gain	Duplication of 17q12 including HNF1B is associated with highly variable clinical phenotypes ranging from apparently unaffected to expression of a variety of clinical features that may include hypotonia, microcephaly, developmental delay/intellectual disability (including speech delay), autism, schizophrenia, and behavioral difficulties. Additional variable findings may include structural brain abnormalities, seizures, craniofacial dysmorphism, esophageal atresia, short stature, genital, cardiac, renal, and ocular anomalies.
chr17	34815072	36192489	17q12 recurrent (RCAD syndrome) region (includes HNF1B)	loss	" Deletion of the 17q12 region is associated with a variable clinical phenotype that includes renal cysts and diabetes (RCAD) syndrome. Clinical findings include abnormalities of the kidneys, urinary tract, liver, pancreas and eyes, maturity-onset diabetes of the young type 5 (MODY5), developmental delay/intellectual disability, neuropsychiatric disorders, mild dysmorphic features, and hyperparathyroidism and other variable features. Most 17q12 deletions (approximately 75%) are de novo. This deletion is enriched in the clinical population. (OMIM: 614527)"
chr17	43705166	44164880	17q21.31 recurrent (KdVS) region (includes KANSL1)	loss	Koolen‑de Vries Syndrome (17q21.31) is associated with Recurrent 17q21.31 microdeletion or KANSL1 LoF causes hypotonia, DD/ID, friendly behavior, facial features, seizures, and congenital anomalies. Key genes: KANSL1. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same deletion. (OMIM: 610443)
chr17	58113002	60275809	17q23.1q23.2 recurrent region (includes TBX2, TBX4)	gain	Duplication of the recurrent 17q23.1q23.2 region (including genes TBX2 and TBX4) has been reported in four non-syndromic clubfoot cases. In these families, the duplications were found to segregate in individuals with a range of phenotypes, including severe clubfoot residuals, hip dysplasia, short wide feet with short abnormal toes; however, four individuals carrying the duplications were phenotypically normal. These studies show incomplete penetrance and variable expressivity for duplications in this region.
chr17	58113002	60275809	17q23.1q23.2 recurrent region (includes TBX2, TBX4)	loss	17q23.1–q23.2 Microdeletion is associated with Associated with congenital heart defects (esp. left‑sided lesions), limb/skeletal anomalies, and DD/ID; TBX2/TBX4 dosage implicated. Key genes: TBX2; TBX4. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same deletion. (OMIM: 613355)
chr17	67892996	69792434	SOX9 upstream enhancer region	loss	46,XX Sex Reversal Region (17q24.3) is associated with Duplications/deletions at SOX9 upstream enhancers at 17q24.3 can cause DSD including 46,XX testicular/ovotesticular conditions by altering SOX9 expression. Key genes: SOX9 (enhancer). Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same deletion. (OMIM: 278850)
chr18	1	15751966	Partial monosomy 18p	loss	Partial monosomy 18p is associated with a segmental deletion associated with developmental delay/intellectual disability, dysmorphism, and organ/system anomalies depending on the region involved. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same chromosomal change. (OMIM: —)
chr18	1	15751966	Partial tetrasomy 18p	gain	Partial tetrasomy 18p is associated with a chromosomal tetrasomy of the specified segment, associated with more pronounced neurodevelopmental impairment and multisystem anomalies with variable expressivity. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same chromosomal change. (OMIM: —)
chr18	1	43500000	Trisomy 18pter-q12	gain	Trisomy 18pter-q12 is associated with a chromosomal duplication of the specified segment, associated with developmental delay, learning difficulties, growth differences, and variable congenital anomalies. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same chromosomal change. (OMIM: —)
chr18	25000001	78077248	Trisomy 18q12-qter	gain	Trisomy 18q12-qter is associated with a chromosomal duplication of the specified segment, associated with developmental delay, learning difficulties, growth differences, and variable congenital anomalies. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same chromosomal change. (OMIM: —)
chr18	43500001	78077248	Monosomy 18q21-qter	loss	Monosomy 18q21-qter is associated with a chromosomal deletion affecting the specified segment, associated with developmental delay, intellectual disability, congenital anomalies, and variable craniofacial/somatic features. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same chromosomal change. (OMIM: —)
