chr20	1	26108756	Trisomy 20p	gain	Trisomy 20p is associated with a chromosomal duplication of the specified segment, associated with developmental delay, learning difficulties, growth differences, and variable congenital anomalies. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same chromosomal change. (OMIM: —)
chr21	1	48129895	Partial monosomy 21	loss	Partial monosomy 21 is associated with a segmental deletion associated with developmental delay/intellectual disability, dysmorphism, and organ/system anomalies depending on the region involved. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same chromosomal change. (OMIM: —)
chr22	17392953	18591860	22q11.21 recurrent (CES) region (includes CECR2)	gain	Cat eye syndrome (CES) results from tetrasomy/triplication (four copies) of the proximal region of chromosome 22q. Structurally, this gain presents in the form of a supernumerary marker chromosome (SMC) that is characterized cytogenetically as an inv dup(22)(pter-q11.2). Type I CES SMCs are symmetrical and contain two copies of the 22q11.1-q11.21 region, known as the CES critical region (CESCR). This region contains 22 genes, of which the genes CECR1 and CECR2 are considered to be candidates for heart/facial and neurologic/eye features, respectively.
chr22	18912231	21465672	22q11.2 recurrent (DGS) region (proximal, A-B, A-C, or A-D) (includes TBX1)	gain	Duplication of the 22q11.2 recurrent proximal LCR22-A to -D or LCR22-A to -B/C regions is associated with a variable clinical phenotype, ranging from apparently normal to expression of a broad range of clinical features. The most common features are developmental delay/ intellectual disability (including speech delay), heart defects, growth delay, and hypotonia. Additional findings may include congenital brain, ocular, digital, and urogenital anomalies, GI complications, dysmorphic features, frequent infections, hearing impairment, neuropsychiatric disorders, seizures, and other variable findings.
chr22	18912231	21465672	22q11.2 recurrent (DGS) region (proximal, A-B, A-C, or A-D) (includes TBX1)	loss	22q11.2 Deletion Syndrome AB is associated with DiGeorge/VCFS due to 22q11.2 deletion; AB breakpoints define proximal subtype with conotruncal heart defects, palatal anomalies, immune deficiency, hypocalcemia, DD/ID. Key genes: TBX1. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same deletion. (OMIM: 188400)
chr22	20731986	21465672	22q11.2 recurrent region (central, B-D or C-D) (includes CRKL)	loss	22q11.2 Deletion Syndrome BD is associated with BD subtype CNVs associated with core DiGeorge/VCFS phenotype with variable severity. Key genes: TBX1. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same deletion. (OMIM: 188400)
chr22	21917117	23649111	22q11.2 recurrent region (distal type I, D-E or D-F)	loss	22q11.2 Distal Deletion is associated with Distal 22q11.2 deletions associated with DD/ID, autism, epilepsy, and mild dysmorphism, often lacking classic conotruncal defects. Key genes: MAPK1. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same deletion. (OMIM: 611867)
chr22	21917117	24994433	22q11.2 recurrent region (distal type III, D-G, D-H) (includes SMARCB1)	loss	At least 10 deletions involving the distal 22q11.2 D-G/H region have been reported in the literature (9 D-G and 1 F-G). Several non-LCR22-flanked deletions overlapping this region have also been reported. The clinical findings associated with distal type III deletions include variable dysmorphic features, developmental delay, hearing loss, and cardiac defects. Due to the involvement of SMARCB1, deletions of this region are also commonly reported in association with the development of rhabdoid tumors early in life.
chr22	23119415	24994433	22q11.2 recurrent region (distal type III, E-H or F-H) (includes SMARCB1)	loss	The haploinsufficiency score for the 22q11.2 E/F-H region is based on evidence for a gene (SMARCB1) encompassed by this region (see linked gene review). SMARCB1 loss-of-function is associated with rhabdoid tumor predisposition syndrome.
chr22	23831202	24632821	22q11.2 recurrent region (distal type III, F-G) (includes SMARCB1)	loss	The haploinsufficiency score for this region is based on evidence for a gene (SMARCB1) encompassed by this region (see linked gene review). SMARCB1 haploinsufficiency is associated with rhabdoid tumor predisposition syndrome.
chrX	6455812	8124954	Xp22.31 recurrent region (includes STS)	loss	STS (Xp22.31) Deletion is associated with Steroid sulfatase deficiency causes X-linked ichthyosis with generalized scaling, corneal opacities in some, and cryptorchidism. Key genes: STS. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same deletion. (OMIM: 308100)
chrX	30195000	30355000	Xp21.2 region (includes NR0B1)	gain	This region was created to capture the various cases that have been reported describing duplications of varying sizes of this genomic region in individuals with 46,XY sex reversal.
chrX	43514154	43741720	Xp11.23 region (includes MAOA and MAOB)	loss	Deletions of MAOA and MAOB have frequently been seen as part of larger, contiguous gene deletions, and often include the nearby NDP gene associated with Norrie disease. In addition to the characteristic features of Norrie disease, individuals with deletions also encompassing MAOA and MAOB are said to have more severe neuropsychological impairment. Individuals with deletions involving only NDP and MAOB have been reported, and their features are said to be consistent with Norrie disease, but without the intellectual or behavioral issues seen in individuals with larger deletions including MAOA (PMID: 8613523)
chrX	48306152	52103258	Xp11.22p11.23 recurrent region (includes SHROOM4)	gain	Xp11.23–p11.22 Duplication is associated with Xp11.23–p11.22 duplication reported with DD/ID, seizures, and dysmorphism. Key genes: SHROOM4. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same deletion. (OMIM: 300801)
chrX	53363456	53793054	Xp11.22 region (includes HUWE1)	gain	Xp11.22 Duplication is associated with Xp11.22 duplication associated with DD/ID, seizures, hypotonia, and intellectual disability; HUWE1 implicated. Key genes: HUWE1. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same deletion. (OMIM: 300705)
chrX	123034319	123236519	Xq25 region (includes STAG2)	gain	Complex Neurodevelopmental Disorder
chrX	123034319	123236519	Xq25 region (includes STAG2)	loss	Xq25 Microdeletion is associated with Xq25 deletions reported with DD/ID, hypotonia, seizures, and dysmorphic features; STAG2 loss contributes to cohesinopathy-like phenotype. Key genes: STAG2. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same deletion. (OMIM: 300826)
chrX	153273980	153375749	Xq28 region (includes MECP2)	gain	MECP2 (Xq28) Deletion is associated with MECP2 deletions cause Rett syndrome in females and severe neonatal encephalopathy in males; features include regression, seizures, stereotypic hand movements, and ID. Key genes: MECP2. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same deletion. (OMIM: 312750)
chrX	153273980	153375749	Xq28 region (includes MECP2)	loss	Rett Synrome
chrX	153624564	153783898	Xq28 recurrent region (includes GDI1)	gain	Xq28 (GDI1) Deletion is associated with GDI1 loss causes X-linked intellectual disability with speech delay, seizures, and behavioral issues. Key genes: GDI1. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same deletion. (OMIM: 300849)
chrX	154118603	154564401	Xq28 recurrent region (int22h1/int22h2-flanked) (includes RAB39B)	gain	Duplication of the Xq28 int22h1/int22h2-flanked region is associated with syndromic X-linked intellectual disability, characterized in males by variable clinical features that may include: cognitive impairment, behavioral and psychiatric problems, recurrent infections and atopic diseases, obesity, and distinctive facial features. Carrier females have been reported to have a milder phenotype with learning difficulties and distinctive facies, but may also be clinically unaffected.
chrX	154118603	154564401	Xq28 recurrent region (int22h1/int22h2-flanked) (includes RAB39B)	loss	Xq28 (RAB39B) Deletion is associated with RAB39B deletions cause X-linked intellectual disability with autism, macrocephaly, and early-onset Parkinsonism in males. Key genes: RAB39B. Care usually involves developmental and educational support, regular health checks for organ involvement, and management of seizures or growth concerns where relevant. The presentation and severity can vary widely, even among individuals with the same deletion. (OMIM: 300774)
